<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-105  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 105.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  Nov 1990 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Matching Case to its discrete environments. (computer-aidedsoftware engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cowling, Ian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Experience and a recent survey show that the investment in Case isfaltering and there are grave concerns about future investments.andO;The Coopers Deloitte survey shows that the three major factorsinvolved in the downfall of Case are: the Case selection approachfocused too much on technological issues, not wider businessanalysis; little commitment was found from top management to thenecessary organizational change; and inadequate resources wereallotted for user and development staff training.andP;  It is notnecessary to apply Case to the entire life cycle of systemsdevelopment for Case to be worthwhile.andP;  To use Case to the bestadvantage, companies should match expectations to their ownbusiness environments; consider all aspects, including business,management, and technical; and understand that the solution doesnot need to be universal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringSurveySystem DevelopmentManagement of EDPProgramming ManagementProgram Development ToolsSoftware Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A model for Case planning: define clear objectives and monitor theresults. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>